        <h2 id="?">Pancakes #1</h2>

        <ul>
            <li>Time: 15 min.</li>
            <li>Serves: 2</li>
        </ul>
        <table>
            <thead>
            <tr>
                    <th>Ingredients</th>
                    <th>Quantity</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td> Flour
                    <td> 220 g
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td> Eggs
                    <td> 2
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td> Milk
                    <td> 500 ml
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td> Butter
                    <td> 50 g
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
        <p> <strong> Step 1:</strong> Sift the flour and salt into a large mixing bowl with a sieve held high above the bowl so the flour gets a airing.<br> <strong> Step 2:</strong> Break the eggs into it and whisk the eggs making sure any bits of flour from around the edge of the bowl are mixed in with the egg.<br> <strong> Step 3:</strong> Gradually add small quantities of the milk, still whisking. <br> <strong> Step 4:</strong> Melt the 50g/2oz of butter in a non-stick frying pan. <br> <strong> Step 5:</strong> Spoon 2 tbsp of the melted butter into the batter and whisk it in. <br> <strong> Step 6:</strong> As soon as the batter hits the hot pan, tip the pan around from side to side to get the base evenly coated with batter.<br> <strong>Step 7:</strong> Carefully lift the edge of the cooked pancake with a palette knife to see if it's tinged gold as it should be.<br> <strong>Step 8:</strong> Flip the pancake over with a pan slice or palette knife to cook the other side. <br> <strong>Step 8:</strong> Slide it out of the pan onto a plate.




        </p>
        <h2 id="2?">Bread #2</h2>

        <ul>
            <li>Time: 120 min.</li>
            <li>Serves: 4</li>
        </ul>
        <table>
            <thead>
                 <tr>
                    <th>Ingredients</th>
                    <th>Quantity</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td> Flour
                    <td> 450 g
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td> Water
                    <td> 300 ml
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td> Butter
                    <td> 25 g
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td> Salt
                    <td> 1 pinch
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td> Sugar
                    <td> 1 teaspoon
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td> Yeast
                    <td> 5 g
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
        <p> <strong> Step 1: </strong> Sieve white flour into a large bowl then add  butter and rub it in with your fingertips.<br> <strong> Step 2:</strong> Add a good pinch of salt,  sugar and fast action yeast and stir everything together. <br> <strong> Step 3:</strong> Make a well in the centre then pour warm water, and stir together with a wooden spoon. Then use your hands to bring the dough together. <br> <strong> Step 4:</strong> Now turn the dough out onto a floured surface and begin to knead for about 10 minutes. <br> <strong> Step 5:</strong> Sit the dough in a clean, lightly oiled large bowl. Cover with cling film and put it somewhere warm for it to rise for about 1 hour. It should double in size. <br> <strong> Step 6:</strong> Now knock back the dough, this means to knead the dough again for a couple of minutes. Shape the dough to fit a loaf tin then grease and lightly flour the tin and put the dough seam side down into it. Loosely cover with lightly oiled cling film and leave it to prove somewhere warm for 30 minutes or until it has doubled in size. <br> <strong> Step 7:</strong> Put it in a pre-heated oven at 220C in a fan oven on the middle shelf and bake for about 30-35 minutes. Remove bread from the tin and leave to cool on a wire rack.</p>
        <h2 id="3?">Tomato soup #3</h2>

        <ul>
            <li>Time: 60 min.</li>
            <li>Serves: 4</li>
        </ul>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Ingredients</th>
                    <th>Quantity</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td> Tomatoes
                    <td> 4 large ones
                </tr>
                 <tr>
                    <td> Garlic
                    <td> 2-3 cloves
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td> Onion
                    <td> 1 medium
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td> Water
                    <td> 1 L
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <p> <strong> Step 1:</strong> Rinse the tomatoes really well and keep aside.<br> <strong> Step 2:</strong> In a saucepan or pot take enough water so that the tomatoes get immersed completely.<br> <strong> Step 3:</strong> Let the tomatoes be immersed in the hot water for 20-30 minutes. <br> <strong> Step 4:</strong> Chop the onion and garlic. keep aside. <br> <strong> Step 5:</strong> Drain the tomatoes and let them become warm or cool down and then peel the tomatoes. remove the eyes of the tomatoes. <br> <strong> Step 5:</strong> Blend the tomatoes to a smooth puree. <br> <strong> Step 6:</strong> Melt butter in a pan, add the garlic and saute for about 10-12 seconds on a low flame. <br> <strong> Step 7:</strong> Add the chopped onion and saute till the onions become translucent and then add the tomato puree.<br> <strong> Step 8:</strong> On a low to medium flame, let the soup come to a gentle boil.
        </p>

